title: Fix export issues in parse.d.ts
body:
The two issues happening on import is:
- Module '"parse"' resolves to a non-module entity and cannot be imported using this construct. (Browser)
- Module '"parse/node"' resolves to a non-module entity and cannot be imported using this construct. (Node)

They are fixed by this commit, and Parse can now be imported like:
`import * as Parse from 'parse'` (Browser)
`import * as Parse from 'parse/node'` (Node)

title: Update THREE.js definitions to r79
body:
Update from r75 to r79.

Note about the definition for `ShaderMaterial.uniforms` : 
It should ideally be `{ [uniform: string]: { value: any; }; };` but I left them as `any` because it breaks the compilation for two of the examples :

```
tests/webgl/webgl_animation_cloth.ts(129,63): error TS2345: Argument of type '{ uniforms: { texture: { value: Texture; }; }; vertexShader: string;
fragmentShader: string; }' is not assignable to parameter of type 'ShaderMaterialParameters'.
  Types of property 'uniforms' are incompatible.
    Type '{ texture: { value: Texture; }; }' is not assignable to type '{ [uniform: string]: { value: any; }; }'.
      Index signature is missing in type '{ texture: { value: Texture; }; }'.
```

It seems to be a Typescript "bug" in some cases, there are several closed issues about it, one of them marked as "fixed"... (I compiled with TS 1.8.10)
Not sure what to do about that, but I guess it's OK if we left the definition as `any`.
